<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">12824083</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2003</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2015</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0193-1849</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>285</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2003</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>American journal of physiology. Endocrinology and metabolism</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Am J Physiol Endocrinol Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>No effect of creatine supplementation on human myofibrillar and sarcoplasmic protein synthesis after resistance exercise.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>E1089</StartPage><EndPage>E1094</EndPage><MedlinePgn>E1089-94</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText>Muscle hypertrophy during resistance training is reportedly increased by creatine supplementation. Having previously failed to find an anabolic effect on muscle protein turnover at rest, either fed or fasted, we have now examined the possibility of a stimulatory effect of creatine in conjunction with acute resistance exercise. Seven healthy men (body mass index, 23 +/- 2 kg/m2, 21 +/- 1 yr, means +/- SE) performed 20 x 10 repetitions of leg extension-flexion at 75% one-repetition maximum in one leg, on two occasions, 4 wk apart, before and after ingesting 21 g/day creatine for 5 days. The subjects ate approximately 21 g maltodextrin + 6 g protein/h for 3 h postexercise. We measured incorporation of [1-13C]leucine into quadriceps muscle proteins in the rested and exercised legs. Leg protein breakdown (as dilution of [2H5]phenylalanine) was also assessed in the exercised and rested leg postexercise. Creatine supplementation increased muscle total creatine by approximately 21% (P &lt; 0.01). Exercise increased the synthetic rates of myofibrillar and sarcoplasmic proteins by two- to threefold (P &lt; 0.05), and leg phenylalanine balance became more positive, but creatine was without any anabolic effect.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Louis</LastName><ForeName>Magali</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Universit&#xe9; Catholique de Louvain, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Poortmans</LastName><ForeName>Jacques R</ForeName><Initials>JR</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Francaux</LastName><ForeName>Marc</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Berr&#xe9;</LastName><ForeName>Jacques</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Boisseau</LastName><ForeName>Nathalie</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Brassine</LastName><ForeName>Eric</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cuthbertson</LastName><ForeName>Daniel J R</ForeName><Initials>DJ</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Smith</LastName><ForeName>Kenneth</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Babraj</LastName><ForeName>John A</ForeName><Initials>JA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Waddell</LastName><ForeName>Tom</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Rennie</LastName><ForeName>Michael J</ForeName><Initials>MJ</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D013485">Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2003</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>24</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Am J Physiol Endocrinol Metab</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>100901226</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0193-1849</ISSNLinking></Medl